25|$|In 1857, Dickens hired {{professional}} actresses for {{the play}} The Frozen Deep, written {{by him and}} his protégé, Wilkie Collins. Dickens {{fell in love with}} one of the actresses, Ellen Ternan, and this passion was to last the rest of his life. Dickens was 45 and Ternan 18 when he made the decision, which went strongly against Victorian convention, to separate from his wife, Catherine, in 1858—divorce was still unthinkable for someone as famous as <b>he</b> <b>was.</b> <b>When</b> Catherine left, never to see her husband again, she took with her one child, leaving the other children to be raised by her sister Georgina who chose to stay at Gad's Hill.|$|E
